The Higgs Boss Decorated
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson created a whole lot of excitement last summer, and for a reason.
Indeed, it is believed that this boson participates in the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything in the Universe, nothing but that.
And then, this is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the Standard Model - our best, or "less worse" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - but which has not yet been observed empirically.
But for physicists, it's still not completely sure if it's Higgs.
It is undoubtedly known that an authentic new particle is held, and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, new data unveiled this week at a major physics conference in Kyoto seems to confirm this, but data is still lacking to be perfectly certain.
Let's just say it's a good Higgs, since the odds of mistakes seem thin, and let's see what it's all about.
There is, in this low world, a fatally inevitable law that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
No way to break this rule - and don't try too hard, you're going to hurt yourself.
But even if the physics of particles is a very strange world, it turns out that it also has a law of this kind: Pauli's principle of exclusion, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" consisting of their carats in a certain way.
From there, physicists categorize particles into two categories.
In one corner, there are good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey Pauli’s principle.
And in the other boson, a dirty band of anarchists who have no respect for anything - at least not for this principle, which means they can be in the same place, at the same time.
These bosons are then divided into two groups, according to the site (absolutely extraordinary, by the way) The Particle Adventure, of the Berkeley Laboratories: the melons, which we will not address here, and the "particles of force", by which the great forces of nature would appear to propagate, and to which some of the bosons will be scattered.
These bosons, it should be emphasized here, are not all animals as exotic as one might think.
In fact, if you can read this chronicle, it is thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon, or the "particle of light" that is the "message" of electromagnetic force.
When, in fact, a particle having an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disturbs" the electromagnetic field at this precise location, somewhat like a whistle thrown into a pond.
From this "disorder" arises an electromagnetic wave (from light, or infrared, or ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon - and thus one of the "force-bearing" bosons.
Stable field
The same goes for the Higgs boson, in this difference that it is another field, the Higgs field, which must be "disturbed" for that boson to appear.
Now, this Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, it takes very, very high energies, as if it were a frozen pond whose only a very large rock could ride the surface.
That's why it takes an immense particle accelerator like CERN - the Large Hadron Collider is a 27-kilometre ring of circumference! - to reach such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
It is not all particles, or all materials, that interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like the magnets, do, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never keep itself on a refrigerator.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while others (such as the photon, yours) do not.
Now, what "can bring" all this research, Mrs. Plamondon asks?
For science, this is used to verify the validity of the Standard Model (MS), and it also allows physicists to scrutinize any gap between observations and predictions of the MS.
In addition, there are a number of people who are eager to be found, as the slightest difference could open a door on a "new physics" and dig some holes in the Model.
This one, it must be said, still has huge shortcomings, offering no explanation for gravity (ups!) or dark matter, which forms about 80% of the matter of the Universe (re-ups!).
But there have been no such gaps in CERN so far.
Repercussions
The repercussions of these researches in the daily life of Mr. and Mrs. Tout-le-Monde are more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there will not be one.
Bear in mind: In the early 1960s, the laser pioneers at the Bell Laboratories did not suspect the revolution that their work was going to trigger.
They were interviewing scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed), in 1962 - fired us, initially the laser was rather seen as a "labo gadget".
Imagin...
And then, applications can also come from all the instrumentation that surrounds the search.
For example, this same Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969, during his work in optics.
This sensor, although not at all its original intent, now serves as an "eye" to all digital cameras in the world, and was awarded the 2009 Nobel Prize in physics.
This, of course, does not mean that LHC activities will necessarily transform our lives, but it means that, really, we never know...
