With Bitcoin, all network nodes are both account book holders, auditors, currency issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually made between two email addresses in the manner of an email.
Except that a user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is electronically signed by a dual-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the exchanged bitcoins exist well in the public account book, broadcast throughout the network.
The key step is to write this new transaction in this book.
It goes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge introduced to computers, and the winner of which, like a provisional central banker, will have the privilege of adding this additional line.
This is a file hashing phase, i.e., transforming a large file into a shorter and unique digital footprint.
Computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before "getting" the whole.
The goal is to find the number that gives a particular imprint (many zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other nodes easily check that it is the right one.
The transaction is then indestructiblely linked to the chain of all other transactions; any change would change the footprint.
If, to fraud, a user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (less than ten minutes), only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network - the other remaining orphan because the two have different footprints.
The computer that solved the challenge wins 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is divided by two regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to a hundred millionth, leaving a margin...
The difficulty of the challenge is also highlighted with each increase in computing power.
The life of the network has already had highs and lows.
Websites providing services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins in deposits stolen.
“The fault used does not concern the protocol itself,” assures Pierre Noizat, who just launched Paymium, a real-currency payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also notes the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this flaw.
Weight actors like Wikipedia refuse donations of this nature.
Others, like the WordPress blogging platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron, of the Weizmann Institute in Israel, analyzed the book of accounts and showed that nearly 80% of bitcoins do not circulate.
In November, “Gigantic Soldiers” were launched.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” says Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, who converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, also author of a textbook on this currency, believes strongly in the potential of this technology as a network of transactions.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (real currency) or a contactless mobile payment, but it uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which thus return cheaper.
The bearer also manages his identity and can therefore be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement for merchants, who do not need to install new terminals or software.
They just need to provide an address that a phone can “photograph and recognize,” says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement of questioning hierarchical systems for more horizontal systems.
“It will take time for Bitcoin to be imposed, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he predicted.
The ECB, in its report, also plans to reassess the various risks, now considered high, in the event of success of this currency.
