A constitution at the force in Egypt
This is a new poker hit by President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever around the constitutional declaration, which temporarily grants it full powers, he decided to play his part.
Taking everyone to court, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State had given this Assembly two more months to finish his work.
Two years ago, Egypt relies on a provisional text, which has been amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal fraud.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the President persists in his "autocratic delirium", continuing to "treat his word" and "pick up the right".
On the side of its supporters, it is assured that this is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible, by accelerating the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 15 days.
A very short period of time which forces the brothers to give up their project to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the President, this is also a way of regaining popular and democratic legitimacy while protesting is raging across the country.
Mohamed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote in favour, as he stated in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Especially since this appeal to a hasty vote holds the ultimatum to the Egyptian people: "Either you vote for my text or I keep full powers", they must be put to an end after the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in a strange atmosphere that 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, with a large Islamist majority, voted on the text yesterday.
Most of the Liberals were lacking in the call.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had knocked on the door, estimating that they had not been able to make their views valid.
The representatives of human rights, religious minorities or civil society had done the same.
In order for the necessary quorum to be reached, 11 people, replacing members, were added to the hurry yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Not surprisingly, it is most often unanimously that the articles were voted.
Commentators also enjoyed the fact that one of the only divergences of the day was expressed around... the hour of prayer, some members of the committee felt that the constituent's pendulum was poorly settled.
The text, which was still being voted last night, contains 234 articles.
Objects of all attention, article 2 remains ultimately identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, stipulating that "the principles of sharia are the main source of law."
The Salafist parties, for whom the "establishment of Islamic law" is a major claim, hoped to be able to replace "the principles" with "the rules", which would have allowed for more strict application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been modified is a guarantee of their goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrity," the liberals replied, who see only a blow of communication.
For according to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They are aimed in particular at article 220, which confers on Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular with regard to verifying compliance with the laws with sharia.
According to Egypt’s specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because “people called to pronounce themselves are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
We can see the premises of a theocracy.”
The fears of the Liberals are also aroused by the fact that the next rector of this university should be far less moderate than the current.
"For the time being, there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this Constitution, we remain within the framework of the civil state.
Most of the lawyers who have worked on this text are not olemas but academics, for some trained in the French system" tempera Alexis Blouet, who prepares a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
