Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of the ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of this agency, it is the second member of the former Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had started a close collaboration with ESA in 1994 and in the following years participated in a number of projects of the Agency.
However, the road from Poland to space began much earlier.
Already before the Second World War, passionate Poles were working on space flights; they did not always meet with understanding.
I would like to mention, for example, A. <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld's conference at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on 6 December 1933, during which he presented ideas from his avant-garde work entitled " Introduction to Astronautics " .
The developments of this young engineer (born in 1905) left the auditors cold and years later <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld received in France the Robert Esnault-Pelteria and André Louis Hirsch Prize for his work "Introduction to Astronautics".
This Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great propagator of astronomy and astronomy.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote many works devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a propagator of world-renowned astronautics, his contribution was rewarded in particular by the fact that his name was given to one of the craters on the moon's hidden face.
In 1925 a drain was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
It is also unclear whether the rocket should be used to propel or brake the drasin.
The only information known about this drastic is that of the press at the time.
From 1933, Polish artillery began to devote itself to rockets.
The research was conducted by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.
It is evident from the preserved documents that this research had reached the stage of the trials.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the search stopped.
In 1937, the plans of a photoelectric hunting rocket, designed by the engineer Rohozi<0xC5><0x84>ski, appeared in the specialized press and the following year the book "Rakieta - torpedo powietrzna i rakitobomba lotnicza" by an author named Lelibwy-K.
These two projects were intended for military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all projects for the use of rocket technology were conducted by the provisional scientific advisory committee ("Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all the work.
This committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war ended its activities.
After the war, other works devoted to aeronautics were published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish Astronautic Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautice).
For the first time, it is about a company in the November 1954 issue of the journal Problème, which contains four more detailed articles devoted to aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor Mr. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society dedicated to astronautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that the field of space research had a future.
At the beginning of the year 1956, the Polish Astronautic Society (PTA) deployed efforts to enter the International Astronautic Federation (created in 1951) and in the fall, the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902–1959), became vice president of the International Astronautic Federation.
He remained in office until his death in 1959.
Starting in 1956, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna) rocket, which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first model, the RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
This 1800-metre rocket was 80 cm long and weighed a little less than 5 kg.
An improved version of the RM-1A was subsequently built, and during the summer of 1959, two-stage RM-2 missile flight tests were started in the Bledov Desert.
This rocket was 1.4 meters long and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The next prototype should have been able to perform concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have a range of up to 14.5 km and be used to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all development work was stopped.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed during the period 1962-1965, succeeded the first RM-type rockets.
This rocket, designed with two floors, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they were distinguished by the dimensions of space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a volume of 0.4 liters, while in Meteor-1B that volume was 0.34 liters and in Meteor-1C 0.62 liters.
The maximum range of all these types of gear was 37 km.
In the period 1965–68, Meteor-2 rockets were developed at the aeronautical institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 missile weighed 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.
Later, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
The entry of Poland to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of a COSPAR national committee two years later are still to be mentioned.
As part of the Interkosmos program, Poland also participated in the space exploration on artificial Soviet satellites and, in 1978, the pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimir Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of this program.
The repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court repealed the Public Works Act.
This decision raised a lively debate in public opinion.
It is undoubtedly interesting to examine this issue from a broader perspective.
Economic systems oriented towards liberalism, both in the EU and in the context of globalisation, are based on the principle of more unregulated economic competition.
This concretely means that the different economic entities as well as national economic systems are continuously in conflict with each other.
This results from the principle of free trade and free movement (without limits) of private capital allied with scary financial speculation.
Significant differences in labour price (salary) create tensions over prices.
Under this term, the following meaning should be given: a producer strives to withstand economic competition by importing low-cost goods by "making them more expensive" than the competitor's price, in order to remove a greater share of the market and thereby increase its own profits.
On a large scale, this means for most entrepreneurs: either transferring production abroad, buying at low prices or disappearing. The result is a significant unemployment in countries where labour prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and thereby responsibility for the unemployment it generates, the social burdens of the state necessarily increase.
All this situation intensifies the perfect bad will of gentlemen entrepreneurs to pay taxes and thereby compensate for the economic and social damage caused to the whole society by this race for profit.
This situation is so popular that it is not necessary to provide concrete statistical data.
The scrupulous practices of private capital create in the different economies a situation in which the governments of the different countries are forced to engage in mutual competition in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population in order to attract foreign capital to them.
In other words, governments put their own people at the mercy of private capital without taking into account the social collapse.
This is mainly reflected in the amendments to the laws in force.
The objective is to economically force its own population to accept the dictatorship of private capital prices, especially in the field of wages.
This is due, on the one hand, to a system of economic constraints in the case of long-term unemployment and, on the other hand, to the restriction of workers' rights in the field of labour legislation.
This results in increasing poverty and deepening the differences between the rich and the poor.
In the RFA, there have been public food distribution points for the poor for years that cannot support their needs with their own work.
The number of these people is already counting by millions.
In the context of the increase in competitiveness of the German economy, it becomes quite common for employees to receive such wages that the state is forced to pay an additional fee so that they reach the vital minimum.
Such a scandal has been updated, for example, in the case of employees working as assistants in the federal parliament.
The economic measures of virtually all the southern Member States of the EU have undoubtedly generated a similar situation in which, under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse of society, people are forced to either emigrate (as was the case in their countries in the 19th century) or to invest capital in the sea with wages.
The question here is: where does this capital come from?
If it comes from other EU countries, then poverty will move from one country to another; this capital may not come either, or then a Chinese, Indian, Brazilian, Turkish, Moroccan, Egyptian or African will continue to work for a fraction of a European wage.
This also applies to all of Latin America.
Liberal theory and the media say, in short, that the state cannot make capital investments in its own economy, that the driven economy leads to an economic catastrophe.
Private capital strongly advocates the idea that the state cannot intervene in the economy through regulatory interventions.
We must then ask ourselves whether private capital does not influence and, even today, does not direct, according to its own selfish interests, politics and, by the same, the whole state.
The answer to this question is undoubtedly yes.
The proof of this is that there is a virtually all-powerful lobby present in all states.
The result is a desperate situation in the field of corruption, by granting mutual benefits, in the legislation, where everything is condemnable but not punishable.
In RFA, the situation is such that due to the lack of financial resources, national ministries delegate the drafting of laws to firms of law firms closely related to industry.
These bills are then passed in the Bundestag.
The totality of power does not come from the people, as the Western-type constitutions declare, but from powerful financial groups serving their own interests.
It is evident that the liberal-oriented democracies are now quickly confronted with the situation described by Appianus in his work entitled "The Crisis of the Roman Empire in the Time of Caesar and Pompey": "The State was long in full delicacy and the functions were attributed by violence.
Pots-de-vin, illegally obtained favors, and stones and swords were also used to obtain these positions.
The under-tables and the corruption were proliferating without limits, and the people were going to the elections with votes already sold." ... "Honest people would not at all seek to get jobs, it would result once the state had been 8 months without consuls. "It was difficult to say that it was a man to Caesar, but we started to say that it was a man to Caesar.
In conclusion, as in ancient times, the present society is based on the preference of personal profit, without regard for the benefit of society as a whole.
In its essence, private capital is no longer able to understand and make the interests of society as a whole value.
As a result, today as before, there has been an unprecedented decadence of elites, without any effort to carry out deep reforms.
We must therefore look for the causes of the emergence of fascist and communist regimes in the scrupulous liberalization of the economic systems of the nineteenth and twentieth centuries.
In the current state of affairs, the disappearance of these systems in favour of liberal-type democracies can be seen as a kind of pause before a new stage.
The fact that today’s elites completely ignore the possibility of hundreds of thousands of future human life losses, the humanitarian and social crises we are witnessing today, as well as the crimes against humanity as we know them from ancient and recent history.
The repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution, at least in the long term.
Under the pressure of economic competition, both internationally and internally, the Government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to seek ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is indeed systemic.
The solution is socio-political reforms, which will strengthen state capital investment in the economy, increase citizens’ influence on the government and weaken the position of private capital monopoly in society for the benefit of the state.
