The movie Argo: When everything goes wrong, call Hollywood.
In November 1979, a mob of Islamist students attacked the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and hostaged 52 diplomats.
They were to be released in exchange for the Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, who had supported his regime for decades.
The situation did not give the U.S. administration a positive outcome, it could not, in fact, abandon the Shah, because it would have seriously disturbed the trust of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable to obtain the release of hostages.
It was a hard blow for the prestige of the United States, further aggravated by the fiasco of the attempted release of hostages by force.
The abducted diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following negotiations organized by the Algerian government.
Their fate sparked a wave of solidarity and an anti-Iranian sentiment in the United States.
The Iranian debacle contributed heavily to Jimmy Carter's defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo, directed by actor and director Ben Affleck, describes an episode of this story that offers a small victory for America.
Just before she was busy, six employees escaped from the embassy.
After complicated peripheries, they found themselves in the residence of the Ambassador of Canada.
In collaboration with the Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran with a rock-eyed cover: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a shooting team that came to make footage for a major science-fiction film.
Combination of genres
Exfiltration expert Tony Mendez's plan calls for Hollywood's collaboration.
In order to make the legend more credible, specialized magazines reported this film project, press conferences were organized, and a fictional production company had real offices.
Details of the operation remained secret for a long time, the film being based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is an unusual combination of several genres.
It is a part of a political thriller designed in a realistic way but also a "caper movie", the story of a successful hit, a betrayal - such as, for example, in Ocean's Eleven, Twelve and Thirteen trilogy.
The ambiances follow: documentary-style Tehran sequences (in the subtitled sequences are presented iconic photographs of the time of events and how, thanks to these photos, these same situations were re-transcribed in the film, there are no big differences),
lighter passages of Hollywood, treated with irony and a bit of exaggeration,
and then scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions with costumed men discussing the situation around conference tables, in the hallways and on the phone...
Ben Affleck has managed to re-start his career remarkably.
As a ridiculous actor, he became a respected screenwriter and his acting stopped sparking ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the dark policeman "Gone Baby Gone" (2007) and the thriller "The Town" (2010).
It is also Affleck's first film not to take place in his hometown, Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of a place is one of the characteristics that placed its first films above the Hollywood standards.
Affleck also demonstrates this sense of the atmosphere in Argo where the role of Tehran is "held" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, during the reconstruction of real facts; the initial sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive for its clarity which also suggests the confusion and unpredictability that occurs when suddenly, in a given place, a page of history is written.
Affleck and his collaborators get a similar effect in the fictional scenes (the fake shooting team in the Tehran bazaar).
Too many actions in too many places
The screenwriter must have been content with a subject that in fact offers few exciting scenes, in the cinematographic sense of the term.
It turns out very well, it sometimes adds some elements to the reality and there, the result is not always so elegant (the scene in which the threat of crisis at Tehran airport is distracted by a phone call in America and the prosecution by sniping them on the slope are shot by the axe.
The weakness of Argo lies in its dissipated character, due to the need to show too many events in too many different places.
If it is true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are quite charming in their role as Hollywood co-workers, their characters would have deserved a bigger place and they are not, far from that, the only ones in this case.
Affleck’s film lacks a bit of dramatic tension, it lets itself be seen with a moderate interest, appreciating the performance and retro style of the 1970s.
He trains the spectator, but with difficulty.
As a reminder of a story yet, in some way, unfinished to this day, and as an illustration of the exaggerated nature of the representation of the secret services as omnipotent and omniscient, he does the case.
