The architects of the MVRDV cabinet prove that real adventures are not just a matter of imagination. To convince yourself, just look at Spijkenisse and the newly erected book mountain - 2 photos
"I find this building funny, it makes very futuristic, finally something interesting to see," says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby on the bottom of the street.
Stefan Spermon, a computer scientist in a large neighboring company, tells us, “Yes, it’s really pretty, this building.”
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everyone has the Internet, an iPad and e-books.
Nowadays, no one goes to one of these ringing libraries at all, right?
Spijkenisse, a dormitory town that has nothing to do with the doors of Rotterdam, holds a very special record.
The community of 80,000 souls shows the lowest rate of education in the Netherlands.
In order to give back a few neurons to the brains, the city decided, a few years ago, to contribute to the general culture and reproduce the seven fictional bridges that appear on the euro banknotes in the form of cute small miniatures in painted reinforced concrete.
The success of the cultural offensive has remained limited.
This is how the city authorities realized that there was only one way to get back to the statistics: building a library!
Winy Maas, from the Rotterdam MVRDV Architects' Office, master of bold stick diagrams and creator of mind-blowing and often cynical buildings, accepted the project with its usual phlegm and presented himself at the competition in 2003 with five books under the arm and one on the shoulder.
And while the members of the jury were still looking at each other, distracted and shaking their shoulders, Maas, facing him, stacked his book of choice in order of size to make it a pyramid, and ended his discourse stunned by activist arguments with one: "common love!"
Here is my proposal for the mountain of Spijkenisse books, or as they say, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>30 million mountain fell off the ground.
The building is part of a revitalization project that also includes underground parking, a supermarket, a post office and a few mitoyene buildings and houses for a total of 50 homes.
In early November, the Book Mountain received the second "Best Library of NL 2012" award.
In addition, the project was selected for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
It is thus that this small, ternish burgade, which until now had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian area and a town hall of a stunning cowardice, whose white facades invite to think they are home to a dairy, has been enriched with a contemporary architectural work.
Most importantly, Spijkenisse now owns the first public cultural building in its history.
The Way to Reading
First impression: Eldorado of the book under a cheese bell.
Sure, an elevator takes you to the heart of the massif, but the real joys of reading and architecture open up to you when you dig the floor of the building to discover its topography.
The completely glass-made interior is bright and clear, the Dutch brick floor and elegant reverberations unambiguously speak the language of municipal public squares.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
We are already looking for public benches, dogs and little boys and girls playing ball.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
“Normally, the rays of the library are located along the facade and in the middle there is a large and dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal,” explains Willy Maas.
We have completely disrupted the classical spatial configuration and opened the reading spaces from the inside to the outside.
The interior of the book mountain has been properly arranged: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the center for the environment and the technical center of the building.
A particular beauty lies in the black rays of the library, which are sometimes lambris, sometimes balustrades, sometimes staircases.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even hardened building architects and engineers don’t want unknown materials.
“We wanted to work with recycled materials,” explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, in a response to the Standard.
That's how one day we found in a farm fries an ad hoc waste from agriculture.
In the Netherlands, synthetic membrane of one millimeter thick has been used for years as a substrate in greenhouses and fields.
It's cheap and we're saving time.
The fine membrane is used for one or two seasons, then it can be discarded.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time in such quantities, into plates with a thickness of four centimeters.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the "Landbouwplastic" (KPL) changes color and turns into a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, the smell of which evokes both a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of the 105 steps is the top of the mountain.
After almost 500 meters, the literary café offers us a breathtaking view of the city, as well as Dutch croquettes and pot ficus.
The latter create an atmosphere, but they mainly contribute to maintaining the ideal humidity level of the literary mountain air.
Gifts for the New Soul
“It’s amazing, but despite all the glass surfaces, this building is a model in terms of ecology,” says Trouborst.
The temperature of the building is regulated by geothermia.
Although the mountain of books is located under a glass bell, the sun only briefly illuminates the interior, even on the days of beautiful weather.
The thick wooden beams mounted across the glass facade serve as a sunscreen, intercepting much of the rays.
The ambient atmosphere is very pleasant.
Fully automated stores take care of the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the aforementioned septic computer scientist, has already risked entering the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
Cynthia Bogarde, a professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even describes the Boekenberg as "the soul finally found" of Spijkenisse.
A few weeks ago, at the inauguration, each citizen was invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This measure made it possible to fill the voids of the library which was not yet fully filled (today it counts 70,000 pounds).
The concept is a success.
The rays are everywhere.
For architect Winy Maas, "there is nothing worse than a half-empty library."
“I believe that our invitation has created a certain relationship between each citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it’s only for decoration.”
This is how MVRDV achieved the master discipline, which is called, in the professional jargon, "the creation of an identity".
Spijkenisse has written a new page of literary history.
Even though she may seem young and under-educated.
It is finally a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
