What are the most common sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial ISTs include syphilis, chlamydia and blennorrhea (or gonorrhea).
Common ISTs are HIV, human papilloma virus, genital herpes or hepatitis.
Pubis lice and gall belong to parasitic ISTs.
Which groups are primarily concerned?
Syphilis and blennorrhea often appear in men who have sex with other men.
The Robert-Koch Institute estimates that sexual contact between men is the cause of at least four out of five cases of syphilis reported in Germany.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia-related infections, trichomonasis, candidiasis (fungal), blennorrhea and human papilloma virus are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The rate of spread of HIV among heterosexual adults is relatively low in Germany, however, some 20% of new HIV infections are observed within this group.
In young people, the rate of chlamydia-related infections is significantly higher than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three-quarters of all infections affect young people aged 15 to 25.
In addition, in Germany, the human papilloma virus is common among young people.
What is the evolution of the number of infections?
It is not mandatory to declare all sexually transmitted diseases.
According to the Robert-Koch Institute, the number of cases of syphilis has more than doubled in 10 years: the figure has increased from 1,967 in 2001 to 3,698 in 2011.
