The Mexican Enrique Pena Nieto has a difficult start.
As incoming President Enrique Pena Nieto prepares to take office in Mexico, Will Grant, of the BBC, is interested in the difficulties that await him and the expectations of the people, which are numerous.
Road traffic in Mexico is particularly bad at the moment.
In a city where loopholes are legion in normal time, a safety dam has been set up since Monday, blocking several key road access in the capital and causing real chaos on the roads.
However, the goal was not to prevent people from going to work, but to prevent protesters from reaching Parliament.
Next Saturday, the new president of Mexico, Enrique Pena Nieto, will receive the presidential scarf to become the new president at the head of the nation.
A complicated task awaits him.
Mexico’s economy is doing well, with results due to ex-President Felipe Calderon, but the country is on the verge of a drug war that has already killed about 60,000 people in six years.
“My government has made a commitment to the Mexican people to reduce violence,” Pena Nieto told U.S. President Barack Obama in the Oval Office earlier this week.
I will propose a new security strategy that will enable us to achieve this goal.
Before joining the U.S. President, Mr. Pena Nieto was governor of the state of Mexico.
A very populous and tempting state that encloses the capital. On its land of preference, opinions about this new leader are divided.
A direct man
In the bucolic municipality of Valle del Bravo, for example, it is inscribed in the memory of all.
The premises attribute it to the development of tourism and infrastructure in the municipality.
