“I hope he will be as good as he was as president when he was governor,” Olvera told Congress in Valle del Bravo.
However, this is exactly what the families of the victims of Ciudad Neza fear the most.
Bradley Manning did not complain about ill-treatment, prosecutors said.
Prosecutors are trying to counter the claims of abuse that Bradley Manning was allegedly the victim of during his detention.
The trial concerns Manning’s detention in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense wants to classify the case on the grounds that the abduction of Manning took place under extremely difficult conditions.
The soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors tried on Friday to demonstrate that Soldier Bradley Manning -- accused of causing the largest confidential information leak in U.S. military history -- missed many occasions to complain about the ill-treatment he claims to have suffered during his detention.
At a counter-interrogatory with Manning, during a preliminary hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Attorney General Ashden Fein stated that recordings of weekly visits made to Manning by officers during his nine-month detention in Quantico, Virginia regarding his treatment were not recovered.
The counter-interrogatory -- during a hearing, the defense filed a request demanding that Manning's case be categorized on the grounds that the kidnapping took place under very difficult conditions and constituted a sufficiently severe punishment -- took place one day after Manning witnessed his desire to commit suicide during his suicide.
This military intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The documents were then published online by WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was their source.
At the hearing on Friday, Fein examined with Manning the forms that the officers had filled out after their meeting with Manning, during his detention in Quantico military prison, where he was subjected to maximum prison isolation from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Fein evoked the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that the treatment his guards had reserved for him was "excellent" and that the treatment he had had in prison was overall "very professional."
Forms do not report any complaints for ill-treatment, although officers directly questioned him about his prison treatment, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had orally expressed concerns about certain problems and that visiting officers had discussed his concerns and indicated that they would deal with them, but they did not record the problems mentioned.
"They wrote 'no problem' (after addressing the concerns), and yet that didn't mean I didn't raise any problems," Manning said.
Military judge Col. Denise Lind also asked Manning why he had not complained about his treatment during an interview in January 2011 with the special commission that had met to evoke the suicidal thoughts he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning responded that his intention during the meeting was to amend his restrictive status indicating a "risk of injury".
The military said they had assigned him this restrictive status -- a level below close surveillance for suicide risk -- for his protection and the safety of others.
"I wanted the staff to know I was doing well, and I wanted this status to be removed... so that I could enjoy a better quality of life from my point of view," Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for nearly two months before being transferred to the military prison from the Marine Corps base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he planned to commit suicide when he was in Kuwait and that he had disappeared once because of the heat.
He added that the fact that he was not kept informed of what was going to happen to him or what was happening in the rest of the world was very distressing.
"My world was reduced to Camp Arafjon, to this cage," Manning said on Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in this cage.
Once at Quantico, Manning said he had spent the clearest of his time in a small cell—at least 21 hours and sometimes more than 23 hours—without company.
Manning also added that the only items at his disposal were a mattress, a cover, tongs, clothes and his glasses.
He tried to stay on the move because sleeping or lying down during the day was contrary to the regulation.
Manning also stated that when he was trying to sleep, he had a light in his eyes, lit outside his cell.
If the guards could not see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up so that he could see his face.
Manning’s lawyer filed a formal complaint for Manning’s treatments in January 2011.
Manning was placed in a military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas, in April 2011.
Also on Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation reported in his testimony on Thursday -- that after being forced to sleep naked in his cell in Quantico all night, he was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other detainees one morning during the call.
Manning testified that at no time was allowed to cover himself with a cover during the call.
During the judge's questions on Friday, Manning said he had deducted from his guard's order that he should release his cover that could have concealed his nudity, but he admitted that no one had ordered him to release it.
Manning testified on Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before, as he had tried to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning had told the officer that he could have used the elasticity of his slip or his tongs to hurt himself, but he did not.
That night, Manning testified that his underwear, tongs, and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that at least the judge will take into account the experiences he experienced during his detention and that he will considerably reduce his sentence if he is to be found guilty before a martial court, a trial that is expected to take place early next year.
The defense said Manning is considering pleading guilty to the least serious crimes and fighting for the abandonment of other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing is expected to resume this weekend, with prosecutors arguing that detention conditions were justified.
The Pentagon confirmed that Manning was imprisoned in accordance with the regulations governing the conditions of detention of all the detainees in Quantico.
The prosecutors brought against Manning include theft of public goods or documents, collusion with the enemy, resulting in the illegal publication of information on the Internet, and the transmission of information related to national defense.
If all the prosecutors are detained, he will be sentenced to life indefinitely.
