The UNASUR summit ended without the Lima Declaration being made public
The VI Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the Lima Declaration being made public, although it was previously announced and theoretically adopted by the seven representatives present.
Efe has tried several times to access the document signed during the VIth Ordinary Meeting of the Heads of State and Government of the Unasur, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency initially reported that it would be released after the closing of the summit, and then stated on the Internet at one time that it was published on the website.
When asked about the text, they reported that its contents had been exposed by Peru's President, Ollante Humala, in brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to the information on the summit has been constantly restricted.
During the day, only the video without the sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private, restricted audio session" was broadcast in the press room.
Few information circulating among journalists was given by press officials from some of the UNESCO governments attending the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document released during the day was the list of presidents present, which caused some discomfort among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more important information.
Later, the Peruvian presidency sent an e-mail to the media with the "final statement" of the summit, but it was President Humala's speech and not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the 3rd South American Summit of Arab Countries (ASPA) and, on this occasion, although this was promptly requested by the press, it had also not issued the declaration also called the Declaration of Lima, as it had previously been mentioned.
On the official website of the ASPA, it can be verified that the document was published last March.
In both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to put in place safe transmission systems for all journalists, but they limited information to the maximum.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement between Chile and Peru to accept a judgement by the Hague Court that crosses a different border between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and of Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met at the regional meeting and said they would respect the decision of the CIJ to hear the advocates of both parties in the trial Lima filed against Santiago and which begins Monday in The Hague.
"We will respect and execute the verdict that will resolve the disputes that we are bringing to this international court today," said President Humala, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has always been, and will continue to be, a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of disputes, treaties and international courts," President Piñera added, handing President Humala a hand.
The confirmation by the two presidents that they would submit to the ICJ took place after Colombia denounced this week the Bogota Pact by which it had agreed to submit to the decisions of this international court, following a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua that it deemed to be seriously wrong.
The summit was held without the presence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, which has been suspended by UNESCO since 2011 after the dismissal of its former President Fernando Lugo, has not participated in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was tasked with opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
