Death of actor Larry Hagman
Larry Hagman, born September 21, 1931, in Forth Worth, Texas, became known worldwide for the lead role of John Ross Ewing, better known as J.R., in the television series "Dallas", in which he portrayed a scrupulous, fearful and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as the magnate of the unscrupulous oil J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who had returned this year as J.R in a new Dallas season, died Friday evening of complications from cancer, according to a family statement sent to The Associated Press for Warner Bros., Dallas production house.
“Larry was back in his dear hometown of Dallas, playing the ironic role he loved the most,” the family said.
Larry’s family and close friends were with him in Dallas on Thanksgiving.
Linda Gray, who played his wife's role in the original series and later, was with Hagman when he died in a Dallas hospital, her press secretary, Jeffrey Lane, said.
He brought joy to all those who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, affectionate and talented, and I will miss him a lot.
“He was an exceptional person and he was living life in the depths,” Gray said in a statement.
Doctors had diagnosed Larry Hagman with liver cirrhosis in 1992 and he had admitted to drinking a lot for many years.
In 1995, he was diagnosed with a malignant liver tumor and had a transplant.
Several years before "Dallas", Hagman had become known on television as an ordinary guy in the "Jinny of My Dreams" series aired by NBC from 1965 to 1970.
In this, he played the role of Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life was transformed when he discovered a seductive genius, interpreted by Barbara Eden, and brought it home.
He also starred in two short-lived comedies, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
Among his roles in theaters are the critically acclaimed roles in "The Band", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was thanks to his masterful interpretation of the delightfully hateful J.R. that Larry Hagman had his greatest success.
The CBS drama series on the Ewing clan and their relatives was aired from April 1978 to May 1991.
The slogan "Who Killed J.R.?", coined to entertain the suspense around a thrilling episode in which Hagman's character is almost murdered, generated speculation around the world and millions of dollars played in betting.
Thanks to this, among other things, the series reached a record audience at the time.
When the answer was revealed in a November 1980 episode, 41 million viewers were on average in front of their screen and made "Dallas" the second most watched entertainment program in the world, after the final episode of "MASH" in 1983, which had gathered 50 million viewers.
It was J.R.'s sister-in-law, Kristin (played by Mary Crosby) who shot him.
J.R. had made her pregnant and then threatened to accuse her of prostitution if she did not leave the city, but other people also had reasons to assault her.
Hagman played the role of Ewing as a corrupt and insatiable man but with a charismatic smile: an unhonest entrepreneur and an infidel husband who was trying to incarcerate his alcoholic wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray).
"I know what it would take as an epitaph for J.R," Hagman said in 1988.
It should be written, "Who is the honest citizen J.R. Ewing?"
Here's the only part he's lost.
Victoria Principal, the co-star of the original series, recalled this Friday Hagman as a "immense man, both on the small screen and in life."
It is unforgettable, and irreplaceable, for millions of fans around the world, and in the heart of each of us, who have had the chance to know and love it.
Ten episodes of the new edition of "Dallas" were aired a few months ago with great success on the TNT channel.
The recording of five episodes is already complete for the second season and a sixth is underway, the channel said.
For now, neither Warner nor TNT have announced how Hagman's death will be integrated into the series.
