A course dealing with the "End of the World" has just begun
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and climate warming.
This semester, when the professor of religion Stuart Charmé decided to give a course on the end of the world, he knew he was throwing an irresistible heist there: the end of the “great countdown” of the Mayan calendar, on December 21, which many people referred to as the proof of the end of the imminent world.
But Professor Charming had no idea what was waiting for him in the following months: the catastrophic hurricane Sandy, a tax spree that some have nicknamed the "Debt Armageddon" and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where Christian theorists would see the end of the pencil.
"I didn't realize it was going to be the most apocalyptic semester I've ever known," Professor Charmé told his students at Rutgers-Camden University, New Jersey, this week.
If we analyze what happened in the world today as if we were 30 days later and we told it, it was a very good time.
And one must remember that what is bad is good for those who believe in the Apocalypse.
And he's not the only teacher to give lessons on "the end of the world" this semester, which will, in theory, be the last in history.
At Temple, Deputy Professor Barry Vacker delivers the course "Media, Culture and the End of the World".
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and climate warming.
“We analyze this because these ideas proliferate over time,” he said, and the way they offer hypothetical scenarios guides certain human behavior.
If nuclear weapons fell into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could erupt.
This month, students will analyze films with apocalyptic themes and study how they can be compared with real-life examples.
“I tried to inform my students about what was possible, likely, credible and impossible,” Vacker said.
On the main campus of the State University of Pennsylvania, Professor of History of Latin America Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an Associate Professor of History of Art and Anthropology, teamed up to give a course, simply titled "The End of the World".
"We're adding '2012' to have the opportunity to give the course again, in case the world doesn't disappear," Professor Restall said.
Despite the “imminent disaster,” students must study, create projects and pass their final exams.
In the state of Pennsylvania, the final examination will be passed on the eve of the Apocalypse, which leaves students no choice but to work "until the very night of the supposed end of the world," Restall said.
The courses turned out to be quite popular.
“It was complete in two hours,” Restall said of his high-level course, which consisted of 35 students.
We received emails several weeks before the start of the semester, from people asking if there was still room.
Students, for their part, ensure that the course is one of the most interesting.
“I’m fascinated to see what people are able to do to comfort themselves,” says Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old student in religion and sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, Rutgers-Camden University.
For the fear of the Apocalypse, whether secular or religious, is only a matter of comfort, or lack of comfort.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old student in Psychology and Nursing, claims to have seen all the apocalyptic films.
“I’ve never heard of a class that taught this subject,” he said.
I appreciate it.
But none of the students questioned, and even less a teacher, told us to believe in the end date of December 21st.
“Our first project was about Mayan prophecy, and in a way we discredited it,” says Julie Zegle, a 21-year-old student at Temple, who is from West Chester.
The Maya never predicted the end of the world, it’s just a key date on the calendar, Restall said.
But I recognize that there is an apocalypse-related anxiety in Western culture, dating back several centuries, that causes people to react to changes in their environment by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has caused a rise in these speculations.
“In other parts of the world, people don’t think about it,” he said.
This is mostly in the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University who gives lectures to the Philippines this year, responded quickly when asked if he knew there were lectures here on "the end of the world".
"The Philippines is not participating in the end of the world," he replied, as if it were an exception coming from a higher authority.
We have a grace from the Pope.
Restall notes that over the years, many supposed dates of the last judgment have been discussed, and he states that if nothing happens on December 21, "people will immediately start to think about the next date" or to philosophize about the fact that December 21 will mark the beginning of a period of seven years.
Students and teachers take the date lightly.
Several told us that they thought they were going to parties "from the end of the world".
“Sometimes I call friends and we cling to them together,” said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
